Boa decisão — para Talos OS é mesmo melhor usar Helm + GitOps porque não tens shell nem ferramentas tipo kumactl dentro dos nodes. O modelo recomendado é:
	• instalar Kuma via Helm
	• depois gerir tudo com Argo CD
	• e correr zone ingress como DaemonSet (hostNetwork) como disseste.
Vou mostrar instalação production-ready passo a passo.

1️⃣ Adicionar Helm repo do Kuma

helm repo add kuma https://kumahq.github.io/charts
helm repo update
Repo oficial:
https://github.com/kumahq/charts

2️⃣ Instalar Global Control Plane (Hub cluster)
No cluster hub instalas o global control plane.
values.yaml

controlPlane:
  mode: global

ingress:
  enabled: true

zone:
  enabled: false

global:
  image:
    tag: "2.7.0"

monitoring:
  enabled: true
Instalar:

helm install kuma kuma/kuma \
  -n kuma-system \
  --create-namespace \
  -f values.yaml
Verificar:

kubectl get pods -n kuma-system
Esperado:

kuma-control-plane
kuma-dp-injector
kuma-metrics

3️⃣ Expor Control Plane (VMs vão ligar aqui)
Precisas expor KDS.
Service:

apiVersion: v1
kind: Service
metadata:
  name: kuma-cp
  namespace: kuma-system
spec:
  type: LoadBalancer
  ports:
  - port: 5685
    name: kds
  selector:
    app: kuma-control-plane
VMs depois ligam a:

kuma-cp:5685

4️⃣ Instalar Spoke Cluster (Zone)
Cada cluster Talos será uma zone.
values-zone.yaml

controlPlane:
  mode: zone

zone:
  name: cluster-eu1

kdsGlobalAddress: kuma-cp.kuma-system.svc:5685

ingress:
  enabled: true

global:
  image:
    tag: "2.7.0"
Instalar:

helm install kuma kuma/kuma \
  -n kuma-system \
  --create-namespace \
  -f values-zone.yaml

5️⃣ Zone ingress como hostNetwork
Como queres evitar LB e usar nodes via BGP, faz isto:
zone ingress DaemonSet

apiVersion: apps/v1
kind: DaemonSet
metadata:
  name: kuma-zone-ingress
  namespace: kuma-system
spec:
  selector:
    matchLabels:
      app: kuma-zone-ingress
  template:
    metadata:
      labels:
        app: kuma-zone-ingress
    spec:
      hostNetwork: true
      containers:
      - name: envoy
        image: envoyproxy/envoy:v1.30
        ports:
        - containerPort: 10001
Assim cada node terá:

Envoy zone ingress
hostNetwork
Routers podem mandar tráfego para qualquer node.

6️⃣ Ativar sidecar injection
Namespace:

apiVersion: v1
kind: Namespace
metadata:
  name: apps
  labels:
    kuma.io/sidecar-injection: enabled
Todos os pods ganham:

envoy sidecar

7️⃣ VM dataplane (DMZ gateways)
Nas VMs:
instalar:

curl -L https://kuma.io/installer.sh | sh
Config dataplane:

type: Dataplane
mesh: default
name: dmz-gateway-1
networking:
  address: 10.10.1.10
  inbound:
  - port: 443
    servicePort: 443
    tags:
      kuma.io/service: gateway
Correr:

kuma-dp run \
  --cp-address=https://kuma-cp:5678 \
  --dataplane-file=dp.yaml

8️⃣ Gateway para rancher.com

type: MeshGateway
mesh: default
name: dmz-gateway
selectors:
- match:
    kuma.io/service: gateway
conf:
  listeners:
  - port: 443
    protocol: HTTPS
Routing:

type: MeshGatewayRoute
mesh: default
name: rancher
selectors:
- match:
    kuma.io/service: gateway
conf:
  http:
  - match:
    - headers:
        host:
          exact: rancher.com
    backends:
    - destination:
        kuma.io/service: rancher

9️⃣ Migração sem downtime do Consul
Manténs HashiCorp Consul enquanto migras.
Envoy gateway pode apontar para:

rancher.consul
ou

rancher.mesh
Fazes weight shifting.
Exemplo:

80% consul
20% kuma
Depois:

100% kuma
Sem downtime.

